pr_review_comment_body:
Because the compute in fp16 is slow in cpu.
When the size of  received data is large, it's better to move it to gpu with fp16.
When the size of  received data is small, it's better to move it to cpu with fp32.
It's better to implement like below.
```
if (total_size > 100000) {
	          stored = NDArray(dshape, Context::GPU(0), false, mshadow::DataType<DType>::kFlag);
} else{
	          stored = NDArray(dshape, Context::CPU(0), false, mshadow::DataType<real_t>::kFlag);
}
```

It would be nice to treat tuples, sets, or other sequence types in the same way you treat lists. What do you think about processing them in the opposite order...

```
if isinstance(id_or_link, basestring) or isinstance(id_or_link, dict):
    handler = get_handler(id_or_link)
    return handler.describe(**kwargs)
else:
    # id_or_link is now presumed to be a sequence of str/dict values...
